Cell[CellGroupData[{

Cell["Problem Statement", "Subsection",
 CellChangeTimes->{{3.985846732774418*^9, 3.9858467345266056`*^9}, 
   3.985846803314785*^9},ExpressionUUID->"ed966bf8-4cc1-b74e-a211-\
5c4331dc6054"],

Cell[TextData[{
 "We have a 3-link planar robotic arm (SCORBOT-ER9Pro) with link lengths L1, \
L2, L3 and joint angles \[Theta]1, \[Theta]2, \[Theta]3 (all in degrees).\n\n\
\[Bullet] Forward Kinematics (FK): Given (\[Theta]1, \[Theta]2, \[Theta]3), \
compute the end-effector pose (x, y, \[CurlyPhi]), where \[CurlyPhi] = \
\[Theta]1 + \[Theta]2 + \[Theta]3 is the end-effector orientation.\n\[Bullet] \
Inverse Kinematics (IK): Given a target pose (xTarget, yTarget, \
\[CurlyPhi]Target), find (\[Theta]1, \[Theta]2, \[Theta]3).\n\nWhy a \
3\[Times]3 Jacobian? With \[Theta]3 free, we have 3 unknowns. Position (x, y) \
alone gives only 2 equations - the system is underdetermined (infinitely many \
solutions). Adding the orientation \[CurlyPhi] as a 3rd equation balances \
unknowns and equations, producing a square 3\[Times]3 Jacobian that \
Newton-Raphson can invert.\n\nThe IK problem becomes solving 3 nonlinear \
equations in 3 unknowns:\n    f1(\[Theta]1, \[Theta]2, \[Theta]3) = FK_x - \
xTarget = 0\n    f2(\[Theta]1, \[Theta]2, \[Theta]3) = FK_y - yTarget = 0\n   \
 f3(\[Theta]1, \[Theta]2, \[Theta]3) = (\[Theta]1+\[Theta]2+\[Theta]3) - \
\[CurlyPhi]Target = 0\n    \n   \n                                 \t\t\t\t\t\
\t\t\t\t\t\t\t\t\t\t",
